This started shortly after Jeremy became the leader, and colleagues who, as far as I know, had a similar political outlook to me, suddenly expected me to make a reversal and take a position that I would otherwise never have agreed to, from topics such as national security to the European single market.
Every time I speak in front of an audience, whatever I say, there are insults on social media calling for the rejection of my candidacy as a Member of Parliament for the next election, denounced the politics of the centre and told me that I should not be a member of Labour.
And that's just what I'm going through.
Indeed, I know that I am more fortunate than some of my colleagues, because the comments to my address are generally political.
I am impressed by the professionalism and determination of those colleagues who deal with a flood of sexist or racist reactions every day, but do not let themselves be intimidated.
One of the most disappointing aspects of this era of politics is that serious abusive speech is apparently considered normal.
Jeremy Corbyn claimed last week that the Labour Party should promote a culture of tolerance.
The reality is that we are no longer that broad church and with every ‘motion of distrust’ or change of selection rules, the party becomes petty.
For the past two years, I have often been advised to keep myself low, not just to express my opinion loudly, and then I would ‘not get in trouble’.
But I didn't go into politics for that.
Since I joined Labour as a school child 32 years ago, provoked by the neglect of the Thatcher government that literally collapsed my classroom, I have always advocated for better public services for those who need them most, both in my role as a city councillor and in my role as a minister.
I never hid my politics, not even in the last elections.
Everyone in Nottingham East had clarity about my policy positions and my disputes with current leadership.
To those who have promoted the motion on Friday, I can only say one thing: when the country moves forward to a Brexit that will harm families, businesses and our public services, I do not understand the desire to waste time and energy on my loyalty to the leader of the Labour Party.
But actually, I have only one message, and it is not addressed to Nottingham Momentum, but to my constituents, whether they are Labour or not: I am proud to serve you and I promise that threats to reject my candidacy as a Member of Parliament for the next election or political opportunities will not prevent me from acting in accordance with what I think is in your interest.
Chris Leslie is a Member of Parliament for Nottingham East.
