‘The sea is ours’: Bolivia’s landlocked country hopes the court will reopen the path to the Pacific Ocean
Seamen patrolling a rigging-clad naval office in La Paz.
A blue flag is waving at public buildings.
On all naval bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon, the motto is: “The sea is ours.
It’s a duty to win them back.”
Throughout country-surrounded Bolivia, the memory of the coastline that the country had to surrender to Chile after a bloody nineteenth-century commodity conflict is still alive, as is the desire to navigate the Pacific again.
That hope may have reached its highest point in recent decades, as Bolivia is awaiting a ruling by the International Court of Justice, which should fall on October 1 after five years of deliberation.
“Bolivia has the momentum, a spirit of unity and serenity, and of course looks forward to the result with positive prospects,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians across the country will watch the ruling of the Court on large screens, hoping that the tribunal in The Hague will advocate in favor of Bolivia that Chile, after decades of spicy talks, is obliged to give Bolivia sovereign access to the sea.
