“We are very close to returning to the Pacific,” he swore at the end of August.
But some analysts believe that the court is unlikely to decide in favor of Bolivia, and even if it did, little would change.
The UN body established in the Netherlands does not have the authority to grant Chilean territory and has indicated that it will not determine the outcome of possible talks.
That the ruling of the International Court of Justice falls only six months after the final hearing indicates that the case was ‘not complicated’, says Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law.
And the prospects of a positive result from Bolivia have certainly not improved, on the contrary, the situation may have even worsened in the past four years.
“The issue of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian government,” Zárate said.
The warlike rhetoric of Morales has all the good will that Chile might have completely undermined, she claimed.
Bolivia and Chile will continue their talks at some point, but it will be extremely difficult to continue to talk afterwards.
The two countries have not had an ambassador in their respective countries since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, who represents Bolivia in The Hague, denies that the court’s decision was taken unusually quickly.
On Monday, Bolivia will have “an extraordinary opportunity to begin a new era of international relations with Chile” and an opportunity to “end 139 years of disagreements, with mutual benefits,” he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales, who is still one of Latin America’s most popular presidents, is using the maritime issue as a political crutch.
