John Edward: Language Skills Essential for World Citizens
The independent schools in Scotland have an excellent track record in the field of academic excellence, and this has continued in 2018 with yet another series of excellent exam results, as well as individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other community-wide initiatives.
With more than 30,000 students in Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best service to their students and parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their students for continuing and higher education, their chosen careers and their place as global citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a tailor-made school curriculum, we see that modern languages remain popular and desirable subjects by excellence within schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you talk to someone in a language he understands, you reach his head.
When you speak to him in his own language, you reach his heart.”
This is a powerful reminder that we can’t rely on English alone when we want to build relationships and a relationship of trust with people from other countries.
From this year’s recent exam results, we can infer that languages are at the top of the rankings, with the highest pass rates in independent schools.
In total, 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages achieved a high score.
The data, collected from 74 schools affiliated with SCIS, shows that 72 percent of the students achieved a high score (“A”) in Mandarin, while 72 percent of the students achieved German, 69 percent of the students French and 63 percent of the students Spanish also achieved an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now as much appreciated as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent school programs and elsewhere.
A 2014 study by the British Commission on Employment and Skills found that of the obstacles to filling vacancies, 17 percent were attributed to a lack of language skills, according to employers.
Language skills are becoming increasingly important in preparing young people for their future careers.
With more and more jobs requiring language skills, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career that someone chooses, if he has learned a second language, in the future he will have a real advantage with such a lifelong skill.
Communicating directly with people from abroad automatically gives a multilingual person an advantage over the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation. French was the only language that stood above 10 percent, with a total of 15 percent.
This is why investing in language education is now important for today’s children.
Being able to speak multiple languages, especially those of emerging economies, will provide children with a better chance of finding a meaningful job.
In Scotland, schools choose which languages they teach.
A number of schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while other schools will teach languages that are most important to the UK when looking ahead to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s interest, there will always be different languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers specializing in this field.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares children and gives them the skills needed to succeed, regardless of the future.
It cannot currently be denied that languages in a global business environment remain vital to the country’s future, so this should be reflected in education.
Modern languages should actually be considered “international communication skills.”
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
I'm fine with the fair.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
