North Korea says it will “in no case” unilaterally disarm without trust
The North Korean foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that the ongoing sanctions lead to increasing distrust in the United States and that under such circumstances the country could under no circumstances unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho told the UN’s annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken “important goodwill measures” over the past year, such as halting nuclear and missile testing, dismantling the site for nuclear testing, and vowing not to proliferate nuclear weapons and technology.
"We do not see a similar response from the United States," he said.
"Without any confidence in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security and under such circumstances we will under no circumstances unilaterally disarm ourselves."
Although Ri reiterated the well-known North Korean complaints about Washington’s opposition to a “phased” approach to denuclearization, whereby North Korea would be rewarded as it takes further steps, it was noted that he did not disapprove of unilateral denuclearization a priori, as Pyongyang used to do.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the very first summit between an active U.S. president and a North Korean leader on June 12 in Singapore, when Kim promised to work towards the “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula,” while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea’s security.
North Korea aims to formally end the Korean War of 1950-53, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also opposed calls to relax international sanctions against North Korea.
“The U.S. is urging ‘denuclearization first’ and is increasing pressure through sanctions to achieve their goal in a compelling way and even by objecting to the ‘declaration of the end of war’,” Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is an air castle of the people who are ignorant of us.
But the problem is that the ongoing sanctions only reinforce our distrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, something the US leader suggested to the United Nations earlier this week.
The minister instead stressed three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the past five months, adding: “If the other party to this issue of denuclearization were South Korea and not the US, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have come to such an impasse.”
Yet the tone of Ri’s speech was significantly different from last year, when he told the United Nations General Assembly that it was inevitable that North Korean missiles on the American mainland would be aimed so after “Mr Evil President” Trump called Kim a “rocket man” on a suicide mission.
Trump, who threatened to completely destroy North Korea last year, praised Kim this year at the United Nations for his courage to take steps to disarm, but said that much still needs to be done and that sanctions must continue until North Korea denuclearizes.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no timetable for this: “Whether it takes two years, three years or five months, that doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia believe that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo said on Thursday to the United Nations Security Council: “The enforcement of the Security Council’s sanctions must be vigorously and firmly continued until we have realized the full, definitive, verified denuclearization.”
Since 2006, the Security Council has unanimously imposed sanctions on North Korea to severely reduce funding for Pyongyang’s nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri outside the UN General Assembly and said he would go back to Pyongyang next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last visit did not go well.
Just hours after he left Pyongyang in July and said progress had been made, North Korea accused him of making "gangster-like demands."
North Korea promised this month during a meeting with Moon to dismantle a rocket site and also a nuclear complex if the United States would take “corresponding measures.”
He said Kim had told him that the “corresponding measures” he wanted were security guarantees promised by Trump in Singapore, and steps toward normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard Students Take Course on the Importance of Sufficient Rest
A new course at Harvard University this year will ensure that all students get more sleep, in an effort to combat the growing macho culture in which it seems cool to study all night while drinking a lot of caffeine.
One professor noted that the students of the world’s largest university often have no idea of the basics of caring for themselves.
Charles Czeisler, Professor of Sleep Medicine at Harvard Medical School, a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he knows is unique in the US.
He got the idea to start the course after giving a speech on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At the end of my speech, a girl came to me and said, ‘Why am I only hearing this now, in my last year?’
She said no one had ever told her how important sleep is, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which will be organized for the first time this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits help improve academic and athletic performance and how they also promote their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to organize the course when it was determined that students had severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The course lasts one hour and includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one of the parts, students see a picture of a dorm room, where they click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise equipment and books to learn more about the effects of caffeine and light and the way sports performance is affected by sleep deprivation, and the importance of a routine at bedtime.
In another section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation increases the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
Using a campus map, with interactive icons, participants are encouraged to think about their daily routine.
“We know that this will not change the behaviour of the students immediately.
But we find that they have the right to know all of this, just as people have the right to know what effects the choice of cigarettes has on their health, Czeisler added.
The culture of pride on a night’s study continues to exist, he says, and due to modern technology and increasing pressure on students, sleep deprivation is an ever-increasing problem.
Ensuring adequate sleep, of good quality, must be the student’s ‘secret weapon’ to fight stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said, and even to avoid weight gain, because sleep deprivation causes the brain to give them a constant feeling of hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old from Calfornia who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler set up the course because he had taken lessons with the professor last year when he was studying at Harvard in his first year.
He said the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to make the course available to everyone on campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all students to follow a similar study program before coming to the competitive setting.
Professor Czeisler advises students to set an alarm for their bedtime, not just an alarm to get up. They also need to be aware of the harmful effects of the ‘blue light’ of electronics screens and LED lighting, which can disrupt your circadian rhythm, causing you to have trouble falling asleep.
