Almanac: the inventor of the Geiger counter
And now a page from the almanac of our ‘Sunday Morning’: 30 September 1882, today exactly 136 years ago, for whom can count well... the day on which the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm ‘Hans’ Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method to detect and measure radioactivity, an invention that eventually led to the device called the Geiger counter.
The Geiger counter has since become an icon in pop culture, for example in 'Bells or Coronado', a 1950 film featuring the unlikely at first sight cowboy scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans:
Man: ‘What the hell is that?'
Rogers: ‘That’s a Geiger counter, used to detect radioactive minerals, such as uranium.
When you put these headphones on, you hear the effect of the atoms emitted by the radioactivity in the minerals.”
Evans: ‘It’s really booming now!’
Hans Geiger died in 1945, just a few days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name remains relevant.
New cancer vaccine can teach the immune system to ‘see’ malignant cells
New cancer vaccine can teach the immune system to ‘see’ and kill malignant cells
Vaccine teaches immune system to recognize malignant cells as part of treatment
The method involves the extraction of immune cells in a patient to modify them in a lab
They can then ‘see’ a protein that is common in many types of cancer and are then re-injected.
A test vaccine gives promising results in patients with different types of cancer.
A woman who was treated with the vaccine that teaches the immune system to recognize malignant cells saw her ovarian cancer disappear for more than 18 months
The method removes immune cells from a patient, then adjusts the cells in the lab so that they can ‘see' the protein HER2, which is common in all types of cancer, and then injects the cells again.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the U.S. National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, said: “Our results show that we have a very promising vaccine.”
HER2 ‘stimulates the growth of different types of cancer', including breast cancer, ovarian cancer, lung cancer and colorectal cancer, Professor Berzofsky explained.
A similar way to remove immune cells from patients and “teach” these cells to tackle cancer cells has been shown to work in the treatment of a certain type of leukemia.
