HIV/AIDS: China reports 14% increase in new cases
China reports that the number of Chinese people with HIV and AIDS has increased by 14%.
Health authorities say more than 820,000 people have been affected in the country.
In the second quarter of 2018 alone, 40,000 new cases were reported.
In the vast majority of new cases, the diseases were transmitted through sex, which was not the case before.
In the past, HIV has spread rapidly in some parts of China through transfusions of contaminated blood.
But the number of people contracting HIV in this way is now almost zero, Chinese health officials said at a conference in Yunnan province.
However, compared to the same period last year, the number of people with HIV and AIDS in China has increased by 100,000 people.
The transmission of HIV through sex is an acute problem in the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality has not been punishable in China since 1997, but discrimination against LGBT people is reportedly widespread.
Because of the conservative values of country, according to studies, 70 to 90% of men who have sex with men would eventually marry a woman.
Often, the diseases are transmitted due to inadequate protection in sexual relations in these relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has pledged universal access to HIV medication as part of its efforts to address the problem.
