What is the Global Citizen Festival and has it contributed to reducing poverty?
This Saturday the Global Citizen Festival will be held in New York, an annual music event where a very impressive line-up of stars will perform and which has an equally impressive mission: the end of poverty in the world.
For the seventh time, tens of thousands of people will come to the Great Lawn in Central Park for the Global Citizen Festival, not only to enjoy acts like Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes, but also to raise awareness for the real goal: ending extreme poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival, which was first organized in 2012, is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, a group of international stakeholders who hope to end poverty by increasing the number of people actively fighting it.
Concertgoers who want to obtain a free ticket for the event (unless they were willing to pay for a VIP ticket) had to complete a series of tasks, or “actions,” such as volunteering, emailing a world leader, making a phone call, or other meaningful awareness for the purpose: ending poverty.
But how successful has the Global Citizen Festival been, with 12 more years to go to achieve this goal?
Is the idea of rewarding people with a free concert a suitable way to convince people to demand a call to action or is this just another form of ‘clitivism’, making people feel like they’re making a real contribution by signing an online petition or sending a tweet?
Since 2011, more than 19 million “actions” of supporters have been registered, targeting a wide range of different goals.
According to Global Citizen, these actions have contributed to global leaders’ commitment and policy proposals worth more than $37 billion that need to change the lives of 2.25 billion people by 2030.
In early 2018, the group cited 390 initiatives and statements based on the actions, of which at least $10 billion has already been paid out or raised by sponsorship actions.
The group estimates that the funds obtained so far have had an impact on nearly 649 million people around the world.
One of the most important statements of intent is that of The Power of Nutrition, a partnership of investors and executives from the UK aimed at “helping children realize their full potential.” This group has pledged $35 million to Rwanda to help end malnutrition in the country after receiving more than 4,700 tweets from Global Citizens.
“With the help of the UK government, donors, other national governments and Global Citizens like you, we can make a footnote in history of the social injustice that is malnutrition,” Tracey Ullman, Ambassador of The Power of Nutrition, told the public at a concert in London in April 2018.
The group also announced that, after more than 5,000 actions were sent asking the UK government to improve the nutritional situation for mothers and children, the government has announced a project, the Power of Nutrition, to support that will reach 5 million women and children with nutritional interventions.
In response to one of the frequently asked questions on the Global Citizen’s website, it was asked, “Why do you think we can end extreme poverty?”
He said, “It will be a long and difficult road, and we will fall and fail sometimes.
But, just like the civil rights and anti-apartheid movements before us, we will eventually be successful because we are stronger together.
Janet Jackson, The Weeknd, Shawn Mendes, Cardi B, Janelle Monáe are some of the artists who will perform this year at the event in New York that will be presented by Deborra-Lee Furness and Hugh Jackman.
