National Trust Listens to the Secret Life of Bats
New research conducted on a estate in the Scottish highlands is trying to reveal how bats use the landscape in their quest for food.
It is hoped that the findings will shed new light on the behavior of these unique flying mammals and will contribute to future conservation activities.
The study, conducted by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland, follows the common and small dwarf bat, the brown big ear bat, and the water bat at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment is placed at key locations around the estate to track the bats’ activities throughout the season.
NTS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using hand detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of bat screams and what kind of what does.
Subsequently, a map of the habitat and a report are produced to create a detailed landscape-scale image of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, the NTS’s conservation advisor, hopes the results will show which areas of the habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by the species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management, such as the creation of meadows and how best to maintain the forests for bats and similar species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the rest of the UK have declined significantly over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development activities that affect sleeping places and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lightning can also pose a risk, as can flycatchers and certain chemical treatments of building materials and attacks by domestic cats.
In reality, bats are not blind.
However, due to their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching a prey.
They use an advanced echo-location technique to determine the position of insects and obstacles in their flight route.
At the NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, bats are taken very seriously.
The NTS has ten trained experts, who regularly carry out examinations, inspections of sleeping places and sometimes rescue operations.
The organization has even established the first and only reserve for bats in Scotland at the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, where eight of Scotland’s ten species of bats live.
Landscape Manager David Thompson says the estate is the ideal territory for bats.
"Here in Threave we have a great environment for bats," he said.
"We have the old buildings, many very old trees and the right habitat.
But so much is not yet known about bats and therefore the work we do here and in other locations will help us better understand what they need to thrive.”
He stresses the importance of bat monitoring before maintenance work is carried out, as the potential unconscious destruction of a sleeping place could lead to the deaths of 400 female bats and their cubs, potentially exterminating a complete local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass or disturb them or to destroy their sleeping places.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish employee for the Bat Conservation Trust, has asked the public to make a contribution to help.
She said, “We still have a lot to learn about our bats and from many of our species we simply don’t know how their populations are.”
