Jack Ross: 'My ultimate ambition is to manage Scotland'
Jack Ross, the boss of Sunderland, says it's his "ultimate ambition" to ever become manager of Scotland.
The Scottish, 42, enjoys the challenge of reviving the club from the northeast of England, currently in third place in League One, at three points of first place.
He went to the Stadium of Light last summer after returning to the Scottish Premiership the previous season.
“As a footballer, I wanted to play for my country.
But I was selected for the B-team and with that the sock was done,” Ross told Sportsound on BBC Scotland.
“When I was a child, I often saw Scotland play with my father in Hampden Park and it’s something that keeps attracting me.
However, that opportunity would only come when I’m successful in managing a club.”
Ross's predecessors as managers of Sunderland include Dick Advocaat, David Moyes, Sam Allardyce, Martin O'Neill, Roy Keane, Gus Poyet and Paulo Di Canio.
The former boss of Alloa Athletic says he was not intimidated to become the successor of these established names at a large club, previously he had refused advances from Barnsley and Ipswich Town.
"Success for me is measured by 'can I have this club return to the Premier League?'
Due to the structure and facilities of this club, it should undoubtedly be in the Premier League,” he said.
“It’s not an easy task to achieve this, but I can only see myself as successful if I bring the club back there.”
Ross is only engaged in his career as a manager for three years, after a period as an assistant manager at Dumbarton and 15 months in the coaching group of Hearts.
Subsequently, he helped Alloa recover from degradation to the third division and transformed St Mirren from on the verge of degradation to winning the Championship in the next season.
And Ross says he feels more comfortable now than he ever did during his career as a footballer at Clyde, Hartlepool, Falkirk, St Mirren and Hamilton Academical.
"It was probably really a crossroads," he recalled from the moment he took over from Alloa.
"I really believed that management was the right choice for me, much more than playing.
It sounds weird, because I did quite well, I earned quite well and I knew a few reasonable highlights.
But football can be tough.
There are many things that you are faced with every week.
I still have that, given the stress and pressure of the trade, but management just feels good.
I’ve always wanted to be a manager and now that I’m real, I’m in the best of shape as I’ve never felt in my adult life.”
