How the US-China trade war could benefit Beijing
The opening salutes of the trade war between the US and China were deafening, and while the battle has not yet been fought, a gap between the two countries could, according to experts, be beneficial for Beijing in the long run.
US President Donald Trump issued the first warning earlier this year by raising taxes on key Chinese exports, including solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The most significant escalation was announced this week when new effective, increased tax rates were unveiled for $200 billion ($150 billion) in goods — half of all goods coming from China to the US.
Beijing has taken in kind reprisals every time, most recently by raising tariffs from 5 to 10% for $60 billion in U.S. goods.
China has pledged to match the US every time, and the world’s second-largest economy is unlikely to blink its eyes quickly.
In order for Washington to bow, requests must be granted, but publicly bowing to the US is far too painful for Chinese President Xi Jinping.
However, experts claim that if Beijing plays it smart, the trade war with the US could support China positively in the longer term, as the interdependence of the two economies decreases.
“The fact that a swift political decision in Washington or Beijing could create conditions that could cause either country to fall into an economic free fall is actually far more dangerous than viewers have previously acknowledged,” said Abigail Grace, a research associate at the Center for a New American Security, a think tank specializing in national security issues, which focuses on Asia.
